> Subject: Use of drones and/or ultra-lights in park management and research
>
> SCGISers:
>
> Bob Ford (myself) and a colleague Steve Schill (Nature Conservancy) are 
> currently assisting the Frankfurt Zoological Society (FZS) in DRC/Congo 
> in the design of new GIS-based management, monitoring, and conservation 
> science research methods and tools for two "Miombo woodland & Savanna" 
> parks in Katanga/DRC (Upemba and Kundelungu) that are just starting 
> rehabilitation of systems and personnel after recent wars and 
> instability.  There are many challenges but also opportunities:
>
> See: http://www.zgf.de/?id=65&projectId=123&language=en
>
> THE NEED:
>
> We need advice from partners/colleagues in SCGIS who have used or are  
> planning to use DRONES, ULTRA-LIGHTS, or SMALL FIXED-WING AIRCRAFT (and 
> associated aerial-based systems) for research, ecosystem monitoring, 
> park management etc.
>
> Our partners are dealing with huge areas (15-20,000 KM/2) that are  
> often insecure or difficult to access.  So, we're wondering if some of  
> these technologies might be utilized effectively to complement  
> traditional on-the- ground patrols, monitoring, etc?
>
> QUESTIONS:
>
> 1. What options/companies, technologies were most COST EFFECTIVE and  
> FEASIBLE FOR USE in DIFFICULT ENVIRONMENTS, E.G. CONGO?
>
> 2. Are there groups in Africa you know using these technologies--  
> particularly in Southern and Central Africa who might assist in  
> support/linkages?
>
